    <h1>TIPS</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200830/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-30"><time>2020-08-30</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE TRAVEL</span>
        - <span role="byline">Joyce Teo</span>
    </section>

    <p>Com­mit to mem­ory the pin num­ber of your credit card. At ho­tels, retail out­lets and restau­rants, staff pointed me to the nu­meric key­pad when I gave them my credit card.</p>
    <p>Leave the mo­bile phone in your hand­bag or pocket when din­ing. Din­ers here chat with their com­pan­ions.</p>
    <p>Shops close early, so stock up on snacks and drinks to sat­isfy any late-night crav­ings. This is a good idea if the itin­er­ary in­cludes a night tour.</p>
    <p>Plan rest stops for long car jour­neys. Roads are good and signs are clear. But sin­gle-lane drives are com­mon and you do not want to hold up traf­fic. You may end up try­ing to keep pace and ig­nor­ing the beau­ti­ful scenery. The rest stops are a must, es­pe­cially for vis­i­tors not used to long dis­tances on wind­ing high­ways and driv­ing an un­fa­mil­iar rented car. I found it eas­ier and faster to use the GPS sys­tem on my smart­phone in­stead of the one in the car. If that is also your plan, take along a phone holder.</p>


